1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 Qb6 {This
game is to demonstrate the Najdorf playing style... You should see how White
plays and almost all of the playing style. Remember that the most important
thing in any opening is knowing the main middlegame plans.} 8. Nb3 Be7 9. Qf3
Nbd7 10. Bd3 $6 {This move is out of the main theory - 0-0-0 is preferable.
But the main objective of this game is to show the middlegame style.} (10.
O-O-O) 10... h6 11. Bh4 Nxe4 12. Bxe7 Nxc3 13. bxc3 $6 Kxe7 $15 {White has
sacrificed a pawn but has some compensation (not enough) for Black's king
position. So I want to demonstrate how a superior understanding of middlegame
plans beats a better theoretical preparation.} 14. O-O-O Rd8 15. g4 {White
should open the position.} Qc7 16. c4 Nc5 17. f5 Nxb3+ $2 (17... Nxd3+ {The
bishop is stronger than the knight.} 18. Rxd3 Qxc4 19. f6+ gxf6 20. Rf1 $11) (
17... Qc6 {Was also good, proposing the exchange of queens. And just then Nxd3+
} 18. Qf2 Nxd3+) 18. axb3 $40 Qc5 19. Rde1 {Normally in this Sicilian Najdorf,
the rooks are placed on e1 and d1; but in this particular case a rook on d1 is
doing nothing.} a5 20. fxe6 f6 (20... fxe6 21. Rhf1 {With a very strong attack!
}) 21. g5 $3 $18 {The most instructive and beautiful move of the game; and the
thing I want you to see and, most importantly, to understand... White
sacrifices his g pawn in three different ways, one of them with check! But the
idea is the key of this line... OPEN THE POSITION AND LET YOUR PIECES DO THE
REST!} Rf8 (21... fxg5 22. Qf7#) (21... hxg5 22. Qh5 Bxe6 23. Qh7 Kd7 24. Qxg7+
Kc8 25. Rxe6 $18) (21... Qxg5+ 22. Kb1 Qc5 23. Rhg1 g5 24. Qh5 Rf8 25. Qxh6
Bxe6 26. Qh3 f5 27. Qh6 Kd7 28. Qxe6+ $18) 22. gxh6 Qg5+ 23. Kb1 Qxh6 24. c5 $1
{Same idea as g5!} Rd8 25. Rhg1 g5 26. h4 $1 gxh4 27. Rg6 Qh8 28. Qg4 dxc5 29.
Rg7+ {At that time, IM Mark Bluvshtein (now GM) was just 16 years old. He
demonstrates than he has an outstanding understanding of the middlegame in the
Najdorf. He failed in the opening theory, which is certainly not ideal, but
knowing the middlegame plans he beat his opponent, a very strong GM. That, of
course, is not the idea. Now you have the possibility of playing the theory
part of the opening well and playing the middlegame like Bluvshtein.} 1-0

